%%%  CN, CH. 
 -->

STARS: </p>

<ul>

<li>  Continuum slope & structure: T  </p>

<li>  Ionization edge discontinuities: pressure/gravity  </p>

<li> Line widths: <a
href="im/lum-effects-at-A0-Gray.gif" target=show>pressure/gravity</a>, rotation,
outflows </p>

<li>  Line strengths: T, pressure/gravity, chemical abundances.
E.g.:  </p>

<ul>

<li> Classic <a
href="im/stellspectypes-MBriley.jpg" target=show>"spectral-type"</a> sequence is a
<a href="im/spectral-types-CM.jpg" target=show>T-sequence</a> </p>

<!--  <a href="im/rwo73-Z-deltas.gif" target=show> -->

<li> <a href="im/EMPstars-v-sun-Christlieb03.gif"
target=show>Abundances</a>: selected species easy to measure: e.g.
Ca/H, Mg/H, Fe/H.  
  He/H  (hot stars only) </p>

<li> Light element (e.g. C,N,O) abundances more difficult:  C IV (UV)
in hot stars; various atomic lines in cool stars require high spec
resol; molecules in cool stars (CH, CN, NH, etc) </p>

<li> Ionization decreases with increasing gas pressure: e.g. use Mg I
5175 &Aring; strength as <a href="im/rwo73-g-deltas.gif"
target=show>dwarf/giant discriminant</a> for Galactic structure
studies </p>

<!-- add ID to 73 diagrams  -->

<li>  NB: Derived abundances are sensitive to proper T,P estimation </p>

</ul>

<li> Integrated light of stars allows inferences concerning ages,
abundances of distant stellar populations.  "Population synthesis": </p>

<ul>

<li> Fit full energy distribution with combinations of <a
href="im/1Gyr-burst-sed-t.gif" target=show>single generation models</a> to
determine star formation history & abundances </p>

<li> Use selected lines for <a href="im/Hb-Mg-Fe-Trager99.gif"
target=show>age-abundance separation</a>, e.g. <img
src="im/H-beta-e.gif" align=middle>, Mg,Fe for old pops </p>

</ul>
</ul>

<!-- 
%%% ADD: line give gas kinematics---more interesting here than in
%%%  stars; emission lines give abundances...but of DIFFERENT species
%%%  than in stars, since elec cloud struc determines whether likely
%%%  to have emission of absorption.  E.g.: no Mg; no Ca; no CH;
%%%  Fe only in higher ioniz; but H, He, N, S, O.  Note: O hard for stars.  
-->
&nbsp;<br>

</b>
</td></tr>

&nbsp;<br>
&nbsp; <br>

<tr><td bgcolor="#FFBBFF">

<b>

&nbsp;<br>

AGNs: </p>

<ul>

<li>   Slope & structure of continuum related to energy distribution of
electrons, importance of Compton scattering, accretion disk structure,
dust emission/absorption, etc. </p>

<ul> <li> Less definitive interpretation than stellar continua because
of multiple components, complex generation mechanisms, absence of
near-TEQ. </p>

<li> One test for a <u>nonthermal source</u>: polarization.  Another:
compare its mean surface brightness to the Planck function and
derive corresponding T:</p>

<ul><ul>

<img src="im/bnu-fom-e.gif">

</ul></ul>

where f is the flux, B is
Planck function and <img src="im/Omega2-e.gif"> is the angular area
(or upper limit) of the source.  Is T "unphysically" high?  </p>

</ul>

<li> (Emission) line strengths yield electron temperature & gas density; </p>

<li> <a href="im/O-N-H-ELdiagnostic-BMPeterson97.gif" target=show>Line ionization
level</a> constrains far-UV continuum ("hardness" of ionizing radiation).
</p>

<!-- Show line diagnostic diagram.  Add comments on shocks  -->


<li> <a href="im/3-Sy-spec-Osterbrock84.gif" target=show>Line widths</a>,
positions probe kinematics of turbulent gas near BH, outflows, etc.
</p>

<li> Line strengths yield abundances  </p>

<ul>

<li>  ...although of <u>different</u>  species than in stars: e.g. O, N,
He, S, Fe (uncommon)...but not Ca, Mg (unless UV access), etc.  </p>

</ul>

<li> ID's, Surveys: strong emission line sources (photons
concentrated to narrow bands) easier to detect than pure continuum
sources  </p>

</ul>

&nbsp;<br>

</b></td></tr>
</table>


